###### Extracting and Caching ######

The problem with this is that I prefer for my controllers not to know about the implementation details of how my data is being returned from the server.

I like to use a trick to **extract** this data before I actually send it to the controller.

<span class="filename">categories-model.js</span>
<pre class="line-numbers" data-line="11-13,15-18"><code class="language-javascript">angular.module('eggly.models.categories', [

])
.service('CategoriesModel', function ($http) {
  var model = this,
      URLS = {
        FETCH: 'data/categories.json'
      },
      categories;

  function extract(result){
    return result.data;
  }

  function cacheCategories(result){
    categories = extract(result);
    return categories;
  }

  model.getCategories = function () {
    return $http.get(URLS.FETCH).then(cacheCategories);
  };
})
;</code></pre>

**[11]** What we will do here is create a method called **extract** that takes the **result** as an argument and it just returns **result.data**.

**[15]** I'm going to create another method here called **cacheCategories**, because as it stands now, we're not actually storing the result of categories. It's actually stateless, but I want to actually store a reference to the server result so I can use it a bit later.

**[16]** We will go **categories = extract(result)**

**[17]** and then **return categories**.

**[21]** From here, instead of returning just the call itself, we can **return a promise that has the result of cacheCategories**.

Also, be sure to remove the **.data** in the **categories** controller.

<span class="filename">categories.js</span>
<pre class="line-numbers" data-line="21"><code class="language-javascript">angular.module('categories', [
  'eggly.models.categories'
])
.config(function ($stateProvider) {
  $stateProvider
    .state('eggly.categories', {
      url: '/',
      views: {
        'categories@': {
          controller: 'CategoriesListController as categoriesListController',
          templateUrl: 'app/categories/categories.tmpl.html'
        }
      }
    });
})
.controller('CategoriesListController', function CategoriesListController(CategoriesModel) {
  var categoriesListController = this;

  CategoriesModel.getCategories() // returns a promise
    .then(function (result) {
      categoriesListController.categories = result;
    });
})
;</code></pre>

